* The temporary solution for the Myfunction_2.java:
**<Solution 1>**. Same as the above solution, multiply each coefficient of the formula by 2 (e.g. 2*a + 4*b + 6*c = 44)
The output will be:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/41780406/43525498-86e340e2-95d4-11e8-8210-a41a52aeeb89.png)

    **<Solution 2>**. Replace the mkLt with mkLe in constraint_2, constraint_4, and constraint_6. For example, replacing ctx.mkLt(a, ctx.mkInt(10)) with ctx.mkLe(a, ctx.mkInt(9)).
The output will be:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/41780406/43524369-b0371d40-95d1-11e8-930d-ecfab6a142ad.png)

    It would be kind of tricky because both of solutions don't change the meaning of constraints. However, the right answer can be got from Z3.

* Conclusion
1. We should avoid any coefficient of the formula is equal to 1.
2. If any coefficient of the formula is equal to 1, we should use mkLe instead of mkLt, or the result in the model would be wrong. Moreover, we should get the result in the model and recompute the optimize goal for verifying.
